@namespace Talk.Client.Slides

@* Concept #13½ — StateHasChanged, introduced before the off-thread gotcha (C7). Blazor
   re-renders a component automatically after its own events and lifecycle; when state changes
   from somewhere it isn't watching, you call StateHasChanged() to ask. This is the missing
   piece under the state-container subscribe line `State.OnChange += StateHasChanged`. *@
<Slide Title="StateHasChanged — ask to re-render">
    <p class="sh-intro">A component re-renders when Blazor <em>knows</em> its state changed.
        Most of the time it already does — but not always.</p>
    <div class="sh">
        <div class="sh-card auto">
            <div class="sh-head"><span class="sh-mark">✓</span> Blazor re-renders for you</div>
            <ul>
                <li>after an <code>@@onclick</code> or other UI event</li>
                <li>after a <code>[Parameter]</code> changes</li>
                <li>after its own lifecycle methods</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="sh-card manual">
            <div class="sh-head"><span class="sh-mark">→</span> You call <code>StateHasChanged()</code></div>
            <ul>
                <li>a shared service raises an event <span class="sh-eg">← <code>DeckState</code></span></li>
                <li>a timer or background callback fires</li>
                <li>you change state after an <code>await</code></li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>
    <Caption Spaced>That's the piece hiding under the container's subscribe line:
        <code>State.OnChange += StateHasChanged</code> — the <em>service</em> changed, not this
        component, so it asks to re-render itself.</Caption>
</Slide>

